tip.text:
It may seem like everyone and their grandma is transforming an abandoned East End railway arch into something or other, but you can't fault Night Tales for their ambition. Set in two arches and an accompanying outdoor area that encompass almost 6,000 square feet, this is a huge Hackney hangout spot offering plenty. There's an Asahi beer garden, covered and heated seating areas, live music from a 300-capacity club space, a large cocktail bar, a beer shack, an in-house Japanese Izakaya restaurant (Fat Baby) and pizza (Sons of Slice).

They've battened down the hatches for winter, covering their huge covered terrace and adding some fire pits, candles and, fear not, dependable heaters pumping out warmth. Just don't think too much about that energy bill. Liable to get lively on weekend evenings, head here for a little hibernation, Hackney style.

Where do you go after a stint cheffing for one of the world's most acclaimed restaurants Galvin La Chapelle? If you're Gabriel Waterhouse, it's to a gorgeous industrial space in Hackney to serve hungry punters your accessible take on fine dining. Waterhouse's namesake supper club started out in the chef's Bethnal Green home before bouncing around cafés across city. It's now found a semi-permanent canal-side space, filled with wooden banquet tables, fairy lights, and some seriously enviable flora.

For 75 smackers, you'll get a seven-course tasting menu with wine pairing and an aperitif. Each course is pretty stunning - though the menu changes seasonally, you can always expect innovative flavours that wouldn't look out of place on a Michelin-starred menu. We tucked into a beaut' flamed mackerel with parsley puree and pickled gooseberries, a delightfully fragrant lamb pastille with aubergine and cumin puree, and five more courses of deliciousness. With an excellent wine selection and atmosphere to boot, this one's well worth the slightly-above-ave price tag.

With Jenny Phung at the helm, Ling Ling's Chinese continues to dish out quality small plates to tingle your tastebuds (no really, it's spicy stuff). The food is designed to be shared and discussed in the most laid-back of atmospheres, just like the humble street cafes in China. Now in Dalston fave Pamela, Jenny's grub has gone all-vegan bringing much flavour to the humble veg.

Menus will change but expect something along the lines of stir-fried broccoli, puffed rice and seaweed; creamy tofu dressed noodles with veggies; Doubanjjang mushrooms, hummus and deep-fried wontons skins; and other goodies too.

Founded by two Caribbean Londoners, Marie Mitchell and Joseph Pilgrim, Island Social Club is all about exploring British Caribbean culture. After a few successful supper clubs and pop ups they’ve set up shop in Haggerston for a year, with a killer combo of rum, rotis and cultural events.

We kicked things off with a delightfully nostalgic rum punch. The perfect balance of overproof rum, orange, lime, allspice, grenadine and freshly grated nutmeg create a flavour so tropical that it shoots you right back to the Caribbean if you've been or makes you seriously consider the trip if you haven't. We followed up with some light and flaky rotis, sweet and sticky plantain, and beautifully spiced curries. Inspired by the French Islands, the 'Colombo de Poulet' was particularly comforting with plenty of coconutty goodness and a subtly fruity spice brought by chocho (Caribbean pears). This isn't frilly, restauranty food; this is hearty home cooking, made with plenty of island love.

If the Crate Brewery isn’t quite edgy enough for you, take a couple of extra steps through to Alfred LeRoy, a barge right on the canal. They make some seriously good cocktails here, with syrups made on site and spirits, mixers and bartenders sourced as locally as possible.

When it’s parked up by Crate you can order pizzas onto the barge but the real fun starts when they cruise. In the warmer months cruise tickets are £26 and include one cocktail and a sharing board of (E5 Bakehouse bread, Neal's Yard Cheese, and some tasty charcuterie too). Tours running through October.

In the winter, and when it's not on a cruise, Leroy can be pretty good for some evening work with a quiet drink - as it’s well heated, has wifi and power sockets. Just don’t tell everyone.

Vegans eh... give 'em an inch and they take a mile - this mile being a weekly slot of street food, music and vibes at The Old Truman Brewery on Brick Lane. Seems like monthly Vegan Nights wasn't enough, with queues around the block, so now you can get your plant-based fix every Sat and Sun under cover of fairy lights.

There's milkshakes, pizzas, wraps, curries, tofish 'n' chips, and huge seitan burgers dripping in saucy sauce. Most of the food leans towards the slutty, junk foody end of the scale, but there's still a few healthier bites to be had like the Ethiopian veggie dips and bread, and all sorts of yummy quiches.

Oh and there's DJs too.

This Trinidadian restaurant and rum shack is the fun fuelled brainchild of Sham Mahabir. Limin' brings the sunshine with a range of colourful dishes that reflect the multi-cultural tastes of the island; mixing Indo-, Afro-, and Chinese-Caribbean dishes.

Under the 'Indian' category you might find filled rotis, or doubles (fried dough chickpea curry sandwiches); the 'creole' offers akra with salt fish; while the 'Chinese' brings pepper prawns with soy, chilli and garlic or Chinese chips tossed in sesame oil, soy sauce, peppers and spring onions. You'll be mixing foods, maxing rum punch, and likely relaxing too.

On Francis Road (Leyton's haven for the middle classes) sits a wine shop and grocers called Yardarm, and right next to that a sweet little restaurant branch of the business. It's small, slick, and stylish - with dark green walls and fancy olive chairs, and it's currently under the talented hands of the seasonally minded, pastry trained Henrietta Inman.

By day food is of the high-class café variety with plenty of upmarket quiches, soups and cakes, and healthy-but-decadent brunches. Dinner (on Thursdays and Fridays) is seen to with high-qual, hearty and seasonal plates at fairly reasonable prices. Veggie dishes are banging here - celery gratin with soda bread crumbs, sunflower seeds and braised lentils should see you right on a cold evening.

In a world of meat imitation and gluten-heavy fillers, this (five month) vegan pop up aims to bring the focus back on what really matters: tasty and ethically sourced veggies. Worthier still, they've adopted a 'root to stem' ethos (basically not wasting any edible bits); and made most of the dishes gluten free too.

If that all sounds a bit much now, it won't once you've tried a selection of their wares, from healthful yet comforting butternut squash curry to a citrusy broccoli and pear salad with plenty of bite and bitter radicchio leaves. We relished in the textural pleasures of pickled and roasted carrots served with an impressively creamy hummus, drizzled with a rather decadent carrot top pesto and topped with a hazelnut crumb.

Decor is smart yet simple, and drinks selections pretty basic; the main thing you'll come away with is a mental note to give veggies a little more air time, and the lingering memory of that remarkable vegan chocolate ganache.

Imad, the brains behind Imad's Syrian Kitchen, continues to lay on his fabulous Syrian menus, whilst simultaneously raising money for the charity Help Refugees. This stint of supper clubs is concentrating on funding Hope Hospital - the only children's hospital in the Aleppo region.

The situation in Syria may have fallen out of the news, but the horror continues. You can help just the tiniest bit by gathering a crowd and booking yourself tickets. £15 of your ticket goes direct to the hospital with an extra £5 corkage if you choose to BYOB. (There's no bar so we're guessing you will.)

It's a stonkingly good cause, not to mention the pure deliciousness of Imad's authentic Syrian home cooking (he was a pretty big deal back in Damascus).
